# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alwin-brück
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:alwin-brück/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] Born in Königsberg as the son of the law professor *Gustav Adolf Arndt*, he moved to Berlin very early with his family.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] There, he passed his Abitur at the Gymnasium Philippinum Marburg.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] Then, Arndt studied law, economics and philosophy at the University of Berlin and the University of Marburg.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] After passing his second examination and promotion in Marburg in 1927, he worked as a lawyer in the famous law firm of Max Alsberg.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] Since 1932, he worked as a judge, but retired in 1933, stating he did not want to join the Nazi Party.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] Thus, he joined the law firm of Fritz Schönberg in Berlin, helping (among others) Wilhelm Leuschner and Theodor Leipart.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] After being classified as half Jewish, Arndt was forced to compulsory labour in the Organisation Todt.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] In August 1945, Arndt was approved as a lawyer and notary in Marburg.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] In November 1945, he became Ministerialrat (Head of Division) of Criminal law at the Ministry of Justice of Hesse.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] Arndt was married to Ruth Arndt (1901–1989), born Helbing.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] His son is Claus Arndt, a member of the Bundestag from 1968–72 and 1974–76.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] His estate is at the archive of social democracy of the Friedrich Ebert Foundation.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] Since 1945, Arndt was a member of the SPD.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] In the 1950s, he was a member of the management and participated in creating the Godesberg Program.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] In 1948 and 1949, he was a member of the economic council of the Bizone, chairing the board for law, clerk law and "DM-Eröffnungsbilanz" (statement of the financial conditions for the Deutsche Mark).
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] From 1949 to 1969, Arndt was a member of the Bundestag for the SPD.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] From 1949–61, he served as corporate attorney and secretary of the SPD faction.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] In addition to that, he served in 1951/52 as deputy managing director of the Bundestag board for Law and Constitutional law as well as deputy managing director of the Bundestag board for reviewing the federal administration (the so-called *Platow-Ausschuss*).
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] From 1953 to 1961, he chaired the research group "Rechtswesen" of the SPD faction.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] Arndt is most famous for his speech in the debate about statute-barred prosecution of Nazi crimes, in which he states that morally feels guilty about taking part in those crimes.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] In many cases, Arndt represented the SPD faction before the Bundesverfassungsgericht.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-arndt] From 11 March 1963 to 31 March 1964 Arndt served as senator for science and arts in Berlin.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Adolf Spies von Büllesheim was born in Haus Hall in Ratheim, district of Heinsberg, in North Rhine-Westphalia, property of the baronial Spies von Büllesheim family since the 18th century.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] He was the son of Egon Franz Freiherr Spies von Büllesheim and his wife Maria (born Freiin von Oer).
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After school in Erkelenz he studied German law and farming at universities in Cologne and in Bonn.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After university he worked as a farmer and a lawyer from 1960 to 1997.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Since 1952 Spies von Büllesheim was a member of the CDU political party.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1969 to 1972 he was mayor of Hückelhoven.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1972 to 1987 Spies von Büllesheim was member of the German Bundestag for Heinsberg.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Spies von Büllesheim was married to Gräfin Maria Immaculata (born Concha) von Mirbach-Harff, Freiin von Vittinghoff (1938–2002), and together they had six children.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] CDU Hückelhoven.de: Die CDU Hückelhoven trauert um ihren Ehrenvorsitzenden Dr.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] Müller joined the CDU in 1945 and was later elected to the state executive of the CDU Rhineland.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] Müller was a member of the German Bundestag from 1961 to 1987.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] He had always entered parliament via the North Rhine-Westphalia state list.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] The social policy expert was Chairman of the Bundestag Committee for Labour from 1965 to 1969 and Deputy Chairman of the Bundestag Committee for Labour and Social Affairs from 1969 to September 1981.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] From 1981 to 1987 he was deputy chairman of the CDU/CSU parliamentary group in the Bundestag.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-schmidt] Born in Holzhausen, Homberg, Schmidt became a mechanic at a coal mine, then in 1942 was drafted into the navy as a submarine mechanic.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-schmidt] He was taken as a prisoner of war and released at the end of the war, returning to the pit.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-schmidt] In 1947, he joined the Union of Mining and Energy (IG BE), and immediately won election to the works council at the mine.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-schmidt] In 1949, he joined the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), and the following year he studied in Frankfurt.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-schmidt] In 1951, Schmidt began working full-time for IG BE, as its Munich youth secretary, then he successively ran the union's offices in Breisgau and Gießen, before in 1965 he became head of the union's Hesse-Rhineland-Palatinate district, and also won election to its executive.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-schmidt] In 1969, Schmidt was elected as the president of IG BE, on a platform of improving working conditions in coal mines, and preserving jobs in coal mining and at nuclear power stations.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-schmidt] In 1971, he was additionally elected as president of the Miners' International Federation, and in 1972 he was elected as an SPD member of the Bundestag.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-schmidt] Schmidt stood down from his international post in 1984, as president of the IG BE in 1985, and from the Bundestag in 1987.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-süsterhenn] Süsterhenn, along with Franz-Josef Wuermeling, had been one of the leading advocates of continuing the criminalization of homosexuality in West Germany according to the 1935 version of Paragraph 175 introduced under Nazism.
[src:alwin-brück/adolf-süsterhenn] In 1968, he relaxed his stance on the issue, commenting that many Catholic moral theologians no longer saw homosexuality as something that must be punished by the state.
[src:alwin-brück/aenne-brauksiepe] She joined the CDU in 1945, and became a member of the CDU-Bundesvorstand in 1956.
[src:alwin-brück/aenne-brauksiepe] From 1958 to 1971 she was the chief of CDU-women (Frauen-Union).
[src:alwin-brück/aenne-brauksiepe] Her highest job in the CDU party was as Deputy Chief of the CDU from 1967 to 1969.
[src:alwin-brück/aenne-brauksiepe] She was a member of the Bundestag of West Germany from 1949 to 1972, during which time she represented Cologne II and Cologne III.
[src:alwin-brück/aenne-brauksiepe] For three years, from 1965 to 1968 she was the deputy leader of the CDU/CSU-Bundestagsfraktion.
[src:alwin-brück/aenne-brauksiepe] She was appointed Federal Minister of Family Affairs, Senior Citizens, Women and Youth in October 1968.
[src:alwin-brück/aenne-brauksiepe] She held this post until Chancellor Kurt Georg Kiesinger lost the election in 1969.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] In 1947, Brück joined the Socialist Youth of Germany – Falcons.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] He was regional president of the Falcons in Saarland from 1956 to 1967.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] He volunteered at *Saar-Volksstimme* from 1949 to 1951, and then worked as an editorial consultant until 1953.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] In 1955, he began working at *Saarbrücker Allgemeine Zeitung*, where he became an assistant editor.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] In 1952, Brück assisted in the foundation of the DSP, which did not reach Saarland until 1955.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] In 1960, he became a member of the executive committee of the DSP in Saarland.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] From 1960 to 1973, Brück served as a member of the municipal council of his hometown, Heusweiler.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] From 1965 to 1990, he was a member of the Bundestag.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] In the Bundestag, he was President of the Economic Cooperation Committee from 1969 to 1974.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] In May 1974, he became Parliamentary State Secretary of the Economic Cooperation Committee under the appointment of Chancellor Helmut Schmidt.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] After the election of Helmut Kohl, Brück left the federal government in 1982.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] In 1987, Brück was elected to the Bundestag with 46.4% of the vote, representing Saarbrücken.
[src:alwin-brück/alwin-brück] Brück died on 14 February 2020 at the age of 88.
